ce:section.ce:para:
Many researchers have used turmeric powder to reveal latent fingerprints as it is easily available, cheap, non-toxic [15,21–24]. The turmeric powder is yellowish-brown in color and is largely used as a food colourant and flavour enhancer. The main constituent responsible for the colour and aroma of the turmeric powder is 1,7-bis-(4-hydroxy-3-methoxy-phenyl)-hepta-1,6-diene-3,5-dione also known as curcumin [25] (Fig. 1
                        ). Garg et al. [15] applied turmeric powder to treat latent fingerprints for the first time. The turmeric powder performed well on a variety of surfaces (Fig. 2
                        ), with the exception of skin, which had a poor contrast. Hence, the authors suggested using this powder on surfaces with high contrast. The formation of hydrogen bonds between the fatty acids/glycerides of sebum and the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups of the curcumin component of turmeric powder has been proposed as a possible reason for the adherence of turmeric powder to latent fingermarks.

Seerat et al. [22] used red chilli, turmeric, marigold, black charcoal powders and mustard oil soot to try to develop latent fingerprints on various non-porous surfaces. The major constituents of red chilli powder are ascorbic acid, guanidine, cis-linoleic acid, and capsaicin (Fig. 5
                        ). Better results were obtained again with turmeric powder as already demonstrated by Garg et al. [15] and Rohatgi et al. [21]
                        . On the other hand, due to the poor adherence, the red chilli powder failed to develop any visible print on the non-porous surfaces under study.

In another study, Dhunna et al. [23] have tested the ability of turmeric, garam masala, cumin, coriander, kitchen king masala, red chilli powders and gram flour (flour made from chickpeas) to visualize latent fingerprints. The ingredients of garam masala vary in different regions. Most commonly it is composed of cumin, coriander, black pepper, cardamom and cinnamon. The strong aroma of cumin powder is due to its major constituent cuminaldehyde (Fig. 6
                        ). Cardamom is mainly composed of α-terpineol, myrcene, limonene, and menthone, the chemical structures of which are given in Fig. 7
                        . On the other hand, the major chemical compounds present in the cinnamon powder are trans-cinnamaldehyde and eugenol (Fig. 8
                        ). Coriander powder mainly consists of linalool and its structure is depicted in Fig. 9
                        . The principal compound of pepper is piperine as shown in Fig. 10
                        . The major chemical constituent of gram flour or wheat flour is starch. The use of gram flour yielded better results, according to the authors (Fig. 11
                        ). As claimed by the authors, the combination of amylase, the major constituent of gram flour and the fat deposits of the fingerprints could be the possible reason for the good contrast obtained by the application of gram flour to the latent prints. Partial identifiable ridge patterns were obtained on the use of cumin and red chilli. On the other hand, the ridge patterns are less identifiable when using garam masala, kitchen king masala, and coriander powder.

Another research group, Jossan et al. [28] have employed various household food powders such as baking powder, gram powder, cornflour, chocolate powder (made from roasted, ground cacao seeds, usually sweetened and flavored), dry ginger powder (composed mainly of zingerone, shogaol, and gingerol as shown in Fig. 12
                        ), refined wheat powder, custard powder and dry mango powder (major constituents are carbohydrates, flavanols, carotenoids, a unique xanthonoid called mangiferin (shown in Fig. 13
                        ), etc.) to reveal latent fingerprints. Among these non-conventional powders, custard powder, baking powder, and cornflour showed better ridge details on all the substrates under investigation. According to the authors, no single powder has been found to be suitable for all types of substrates under all circumstances.

Kumari et al. [16] attempted to decipher latent fingerprints of sweat and sebum using common food colourants and reported preliminary results. Orange-red (having dye content 30.2% and main ingredients are: Sodium chloride, Sunset Yellow FCF, and Carmoisine), lemon yellow (having dye content 22.2% and ingredients are: Sodium chloride, Tartrazine), and bright green (having dye content 17.2% and ingredients are: Sodium chloride, Tartrazine, Brilliant Blue FCF) food colours were used in this study. The structures of the chemical constituents of the food colours are presented in Fig. 14
                        . The aluminium matrices produced clear results (Fig. 15
                        ) out of the various surfaces under examination.

Anand et al. [32] have demonstrated various cosmetic materials such as bleach activator, eye shadow, face pack and face powder as fingerprint developing agents on various porous and non-porous substrates. The essential ingredients of a bleach activator are aluminium starch octenylsuccinate and ammonium bicarbonate (NH4HCO3). The aluminium starch octenylsuccinate (Fig. 18
                        ) is produced by the reaction of octenyl succinic anhydride with starch [37]. The eye shadow is primarily composed of petroleum jelly, fatty acids, lanoline, carmine (Fig. 19
                        ), titanium dioxide (TiO2), bismuth oxychloride (BiOCl), and other ingredients. [38]. It is noteworthy that titanium dioxide is used as a base in the formulation of conventional white colour fingerprint powders. The face masks are developed for different skin types: oily, dry and normal. The face powders are mainly composed of titanium dioxide or zinc oxide (ZnO) and bismuth oxychloride.

Badiye et al. [55] and Jossan et al. [28] demonstrated the efficacy of Robin® powder blue, a fabric whitener as a fingerprint powder. The major component of the Robin® powder blue is an ultramarine blue pigment, which is a complex inorganic compound formerly obtained from lapis lazuli, a deep-blue metamorphic rock. Nowadays, it is prepared artificially. The presence of trisulfur radical anion (S3
                        •–) is responsible for the blue colour of the pigment. The approximate chemical formula of the ultramarine pigment is Na6–10Al6Si6O24S2–4 or 3Na2O⋅2Al2⋅6SiO2⋅2Na2S or 3Na2O⋅3Al2O3⋅6SiO2⋅2Na2S which can vary with the manufacturing conditions, purity and the different proportions of the ingredients [56]. The fingerprints developed by Robin® powder blue by Badiye et al. [55] demonstrated excellent contrast on a wide range of non-porous, porous and semi-porous surfaces (Fig. 21
                        ). The minutiae features of the Robin® powder blue-developed fingerprints were clearly visible. The commercial version of this blue powder “Ranipal” performed better on various surfaces such as aluminium foil, compact disc, glass, plywood, fiberglass, transparency sheet, and aluminium can compared to other non-conventional powders as reported by Jossan et al. [28].
